"Matthews H.D., Turner S.E.","Of mongooses and mitigation: Ecological analogues to geoengineering",2009,"Environmental Research Letters","4","4", 045105,"","",,,10.1088/1748-9326/4/4/045105,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70749145229&partnerID=40&md5=572d8822741def6a19f6d1b2e29138ef","Department of Geography, Planning and Environment, Concordia University, 1455 de Maisonneuve W, Montreal, QC H3G 1M8, Canada; Department of Anthropology, University of Calgary, Calgary, Canada","Matthews, H.D., Department of Geography, Planning and Environment, Concordia University, 1455 de Maisonneuve W, Montreal, QC H3G 1M8, Canada; Turner, S.E., Department of Anthropology, University of Calgary, Calgary, Canada","Anthropogenic global warming is a growing environmental problem resulting from unintentional human intervention in the global climate system. If employed as a response strategy, geoengineering would represent an additional intentional human intervention in the climate system, with the intent of decreasing net climate impacts. There is a rich and fascinating history of human intervention in environmental systems, with many specific examples from ecology of deliberate human intervention aimed at correcting or decreasing the impact of previous unintentionally created problems. Additional interventions do not always bring the intended results, and in many cases there is evidence that net impacts have increased with the degree of human intervention. In this letter, we report some of the examples in the scientific literature that have documented such human interventions in environmental systems, which may serve as analogues to geoengineering. We argue that a high degree of system understanding is required for increased intervention to lead to decreased impacts. Given our current level of understanding of the climate system, it is likely that the result of at least some geoengineering efforts would follow previous ecological examples where increased human intervention has led to an overall increase in negative environmental consequences. © 2009 IOP Publishing Ltd.","Biological control; Climate change; Climate engineering; Ecological intervention","Climate change; Global warming; Anthropogenic global warming; Biological controls; Ecological intervention; Environmental consequences; Environmental problems; Environmental systems; Global climate system; Scientific literature; Ecology",,,,,,"Baldwin, P.H., Schwartz, C.W., Schwartz, E.R., Life history and economic status of the mongoose in Hawaii (1952) J. Mammal., 33 (3), pp. 335-356; Barrett, S., The incredible economics of geoengineering (2008) Environ. Resour. Econ., 39 (1), pp. 45-54; Blowes, D.W., Ptacek, C.J., Benner, S.G., McRae, C.W.T., Bennett, T.A., Puls, R.W., Treatment of inorganic contaminants using permeable reactive barriers (2000) J. Contam. Hydrol., 45 (1-2), pp. 123-137; Byers, J.E., Cuddington, K., Jones, C.G., Talley, T.S., Hastings, A., Lambrinos, J.G., Crooks, J.A., Wilson, W.G., Using ecosystem engineers to restore ecological systems (2006) Trends Ecol. Evol., 21 (9), pp. 493-500; Caltagirone, L.E., Landmark examples in classical biological control (1981) Ann. Rev. Entomol., 26 (1), pp. 213-232; Carlin, A., Global climate change control: Is there a better strategy than reducing greenhouse gas emission? (2007) Law Rev., 155, pp. 1401-1497; Caro, T., The Pleistocene re-wilding gambit (2007) Trends Ecol. Evol., 22 (6), pp. 281-283; Carson, R., (1962) Silent Spring; Cheng, S., Grosse, W., Karrenbrock, F., Thoennessen, M., Efficiency of constructed wetlands in decontamination of water polluted by heavy metals (2002) Ecol. Eng., 18 (3), pp. 317-325; Civeyrel, L., Simberloff, D., A tale of two snails: Is the cure worse than the disease? (1996) Biodivers. Conserv., 5 (10), pp. 1231-1252; Clarke, B., Murray, J., Johnson, M.S., The extinction of endemic species by a program of biological control (1984) Pacific Sci., 38, pp. 97-104; Coblentz, B.E., Coblentz, B.A., 